    <!-- 01 CONTEXT -->
    <div class="panel active" id="panel-context">
      <div class="panel-eyebrow">What Ownly is</div>
      <h2>A logistics company using its idle fleet to break a duopoly's pricing model</h2>
      <p>Ownly is Rapido's standalone food delivery app, piloted from August 2025 in Koramangala, HSR Layout, and BTM Layout, then launched city-wide across Bengaluru on <strong>March 3, 2026</strong>. The structural premise: <em>Rapido already delivers food for Zomato and Swiggy as a third-party logistics partner.</em> Ownly is the attempt to cut the intermediary and own the customer relationship directly.</p>
      <p>The model's core positioning is <strong>zero commission to restaurants</strong>. Where Zomato charges 18–28% and Swiggy 17–25%, Ownly charges nothing. Revenue comes entirely from a flat ₹30 delivery fee paid by the customer. Restaurants keep 100% of food revenue, prices match dine-in, and there are no packaging mark-ups or platform fees. The "Food Promise" campaign — a satirical courtroom ad putting hidden charges on trial — went viral with restaurant owners and positioned Ownly as the verdict against a broken system.</p>

      <div class="finding-grid">
        <div class="finding-card good">
          <div class="finding-title">The structural advantage</div>
          <div class="finding-body">Rapido's 9M+ Captain network already delivers food for incumbents. Bike-taxi demand drops ~50% during lunch hours — Ownly fills that idle time with food orders. No fleet build from scratch, no incremental Captain recruiting cost.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="finding-card good">
          <div class="finding-title">The 70K restaurant gap</div>
          <div class="finding-body">Bengaluru has 1L+ FSSAI-licensed restaurants. Fewer than 30K are on Swiggy or Zomato. Ownly targets the invisible 70K — offline restaurants the incumbents never courted, much like Rapido did with offline autorickshaw drivers.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="finding-card mid">
          <div class="finding-title">Perfect timing window</div>
          <div class="finding-body">India's Online Gaming Act (Aug 2025) banned real-money gaming, freeing habitual app-spending attention. Zomato's platform fee hit ₹14.90 in March 2026 (from ₹2 in 2023). User anger at incumbents peaked at exactly the moment Ownly launched.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="finding-card bad">
          <div class="finding-title">The revenue problem</div>
          <div class="finding-body">₹30/order is the only income stream. At 5,000 daily orders that's ₹54.75L/month gross before delivery costs. With captain payouts of ₹40–70/order, Ownly is almost certainly losing ₹10–25 per order. This is a deliberate acquisition strategy — but it needs an exit.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout">
        <b>Why this teardown exists</b>
        Ownly is one of the most interesting PM problems in Indian consumer tech right now — not because it's guaranteed to work, but because it's a genuine structural bet rather than a feature launch. The zero-commission promise, the offline restaurant play, and the idle-fleet economics each deserve stress-testing separately. This is that stress test.
      </div>

