      <p>The customer price advantage is documented and real — the same pizza cost ₹124.95 on Ownly vs ₹191 on Zomato when a Bengaluru user ran the comparison on launch day. <strong>That's a 35% total bill reduction</strong>, which is a compelling switching reason. But a 35% price cut only works as a moat if you can sustain the economics at scale — and right now, Ownly cannot.</p>

      <div class="callout ink">
        <b>The Meesho analogy — what holds and what doesn't</b>
        Aravind Sanka explicitly compares Ownly to Meesho — not competing for Zomato's existing users, but unlocking the offline 70K. The supply-side analogy holds: Meesho unlocked sellers that Flipkart ignored; Ownly is unlocking restaurants that Zomato ignored. But the demand-side analogy breaks: <strong>Meesho's customer acquisition cost was near-zero via WhatsApp social commerce</strong>. Ownly needs app downloads and individual user switching — both of which have a higher cost floor. The offline restaurants are an opportunity. They are not, by themselves, a demand-generation engine.
      </div>

