    <!-- 05 RISKS -->
    <div class="panel" id="panel-risks">
      <div class="panel-eyebrow">What's not working</div>
      <h2>Four structural problems the current model hasn't solved</h2>
      <p>Early traction is real but fragile. Each of these is a load-bearing wall — ignore any one and the model collapses at scale.</p>

      <div class="journey">
        <div class="j-step">
          <div class="j-num terra">1</div>
          <div class="j-content">
            <h3>₹30/order is not a business model at scale</h3>
            <p>At 5,000 daily orders, gross revenue is ~₹54.75L/month. Estimated delivery cost (captain payout + fuel + tech) is ₹50–70/order. <strong>Ownly is almost certainly losing ₹20–40 per order before any G&A cost.</strong> That's acceptable as a launch subsidy. It is not acceptable at 500,000 daily orders without a parallel revenue stream. The math simply doesn't close on delivery fees alone — even Zomato and Swiggy, with 20–30% commissions, only achieved near-profitability after a decade of scale.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="j-step">
          <div class="j-num terra">2</div>
          <div class="j-content">
            <h3>Consumer switching cost is higher than it looks</h3>
            <p>Zomato Gold and Swiggy One create subscription-locked loyalty — users pre-pay for annual/monthly benefits and won't leave mid-cycle. Beyond subscriptions, <strong>two years of order history, saved addresses, favourite restaurants, and wish lists don't transfer</strong>. A ₹65 saving per order is compelling. But it isn't always enough to overcome the inertia of a fully-configured Zomato account with 200+ order history and Gold benefits active.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="j-step">
          <div class="j-num terra">3</div>
          <div class="j-content">
            <h3>Offline restaurants are offline for a reason</h3>
            <p>Rapido's CEO frames the unserved 70K as an opportunity analogous to offline autorickshaws. But autorickshaws were offline because they lacked a booking app — demand was there. Many offline restaurants are offline because their volume is too low to justify operational complexity. <strong>A restaurant doing 10 covers a day doesn't automatically become viable at 50 online orders because commission is zero.</strong> Food quality consistency, packaging, and delivery-window management are operational skills many small restaurants haven't built. Onboarding them doesn't create order volume from nothing.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="j-step">
          <div class="j-num terra">4</div>
          <div class="j-content">
            <h3>The commission creep credibility problem</h3>
            <p>Zomato launched with zero commissions in 2010. Every restaurant owner in NRAI's 50K membership knows that history. <strong>The "zero commission forever" promise has no contractual enforcement mechanism</strong> — Ownly can raise commissions the moment it achieves supply-side lock-in, and restaurants have no legal protection. CEO promises and NRAI alignment are goodwill, not guarantees. This is the elephant in every NRAI town hall, and it limits how deeply restaurants will invest in Ownly-exclusive operations.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout terra">
        <b>The incumbent retaliation risk</b>
        Zomato (Eternal) holds ₹15,000+ Cr in cash. Swiggy's IPO raised significant capital. Both can afford to temporarily waive commissions or subsidise delivery specifically in Bengaluru to starve Ownly of momentum. They haven't done so yet — either because they don't take Ownly seriously, or because their unit economics can't absorb a price war right now. <strong>Ownly needs to be in 4–5 cities before the incumbents' response lands</strong> — otherwise Bengaluru becomes a contained test that Zomato can neutralise with a targeted promotional blitz.
      </div>

