      <p style="margin-top:6px;"><strong>Gap:</strong> Ownly's Must-haves are solid. Its Performance features are mostly unproven. Its Delighters column is almost entirely empty — and two of those delighters (loyalty and charter) directly address the biggest retention and credibility risks identified in panel 05.</p>

      <div class="rec-block">
        <div class="rec-num">Priority 01 — Critical</div>
        <div class="rec-title">Build a second revenue stream before the first city hits profitability pressure</div>
        <div class="rec-body">
          The ₹30/order model works as customer acquisition but cannot be the end state. Rapido's own mobility business already wrote the playbook: <strong>captain subscriptions replaced per-ride commissions and became ₹275Cr of FY25 revenue — a 14× surge in one year.</strong><br><br>
          <strong>What I'd test: a Restaurant Visibility Pass</strong> — optional ₹999–₹1,999/month subscription for featured placement, push notification access to nearby users, and weekly analytics dashboards. Positioned as a marketing tool (restaurants already pay lakhs for Zomato Ads), not a commission. The zero-commission promise stays intact. At 10% of 20K partners, that's ₹2–4Cr/month in recurring B2B revenue that doesn't require order volume to scale.<br><br>
          <strong>A/B test to run:</strong> Split newly onboarded restaurants into two cohorts. Cohort A gets the standard zero-commission onboarding. Cohort B gets a 90-day free Visibility Pass trial then a conversion ask. Measure: does featured placement actually drive order lift? If yes, the product sells itself. If no, the feature needs redesign before monetisation.
        </div>
        <div class="rec-metric">Primary metric: <span>Visibility Pass conversion rate</span> · hypothesis: 8–12% within 90 days · secondary: does Pass status correlate with 30% more orders for that restaurant?</div>
      </div>

      <div class="rec-block">
        <div class="rec-num">Priority 02 — High</div>
        <div class="rec-title">Launch Ownly Stamp — a loyalty mechanic before expanding to a second city</div>
        <div class="rec-body">
          Ownly's biggest retention risk isn't price — it's that users with no sunk cost will follow the next promotion wherever it lands. Zomato Gold and Swiggy One create switching costs that price alone can't overcome.<br><br>
          <strong>What I'd build: Ownly Stamp</strong> — a 10-order stamp card (no app update, works natively in-app) that grants a free delivery on the 10th order. No monthly fee, no sign-up friction — just a visible counter on the home screen that rewards repeat use. Economics: gifting one ₹30 delivery per 10-order cycle on average ~₹600 spend is a 5% loyalty cost — cheaper than any cashback programme.<br><br>
          <strong>A/B test to run:</strong> Two Bengaluru districts. District A gets Stamp visible on homescreen. District B gets a one-time 10% discount on next order. Measure: which drives higher 30-day repeat rate? Hypothesis: the Stamp drives more repeat orders because it creates a visible progress goal (loss aversion), while the discount creates a single-use event and then resets.
        </div>
        <div class="rec-metric">Primary metric: <span>7-day repeat order rate, Stamp users vs control</span> · hypothesis: +25% frequency lift · secondary: average orders/month per active user in each cohort</div>
      </div>

      <div class="rec-block">
        <div class="rec-num">Priority 03 — Medium</div>
        <div class="rec-title">Publish a Zero Commission Charter with NRAI — make the promise contractual, not rhetorical</div>
        <div class="rec-body">
          Every restaurant owner who remembers Zomato's trajectory is waiting for Ownly's model shift. CEO promises are not binding. NRAI alignment is goodwill. Neither is protection against a future commission introduction.<br><br>
          <strong>What I'd do:</strong> Work with NRAI to publish a formal <em>Zero Commission Charter</em> — a publicly reviewed, legally considered commitment with a specific named window. For example: <strong>"Ownly commits to zero order commission for any restaurant partner for the first 36 months of their partnership."</strong> This doesn't need to be a permanent promise — just long enough that restaurants make real investment in Ownly operations (dedicated packaging, exclusive promotions, staff training) before worrying about a model change.<br><br>
          The 36-month window also gives Ownly time to build relationship depth that survives a future monetisation evolution — exactly as Rapido's Captain relationships survived the shift from per-ride cuts to subscriptions.
        </div>
        <div class="rec-metric">Signal to watch: <span>Restaurant NPS post-Charter announcement</span> · hypothesis: +15 NPS points among newly onboarded restaurants · also watch: average time from onboarding to first Ownly-exclusive promotion</div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout green">
        <b>What I'd explicitly not prioritise: quick commerce</b>
        Several analysts suggest Ownly add a Blinkit/Instamart equivalent for 10-minute delivery. I'd push back hard. Blinkit required Zomato to acquire it for ₹4,447Cr and run it as a separate business unit with dark stores and dedicated inventory. <strong>Ownly's structural advantage is restaurant supply and idle Captains — not inventory management.</strong> Rushing into quick commerce before food delivery is unit-economics positive risks Amazon's India food delivery mistake: entering without focus, burning capital, and exiting with no market share in either category.
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- 07 REFLECTIONS -->
    <div class="panel" id="panel-reflections">
      <div class="panel-eyebrow">Reflections</div>
      <h2>What reading this model taught me</h2>
      <p>The most interesting signal in Ownly's story isn't the zero-commission model — it's the sequence of three model pivots before launch. <strong>Starting with 8–15% commission, shifting to restaurant-pays-delivery, then to customer-pays-everything in under 12 months</strong> suggests a team doing genuine hypothesis-testing rather than executing a fixed plan. That's a positive PM signal: each pivot was likely data-driven, not reactive. The open question is whether they've now found the right equilibrium or are still searching.</p>
      <p>I'd also stress-test the Meesho analogy more carefully than the CEO does in press. Meesho's advantage was social distribution — near-zero customer acquisition cost via WhatsApp. <strong>Ownly's demand generation relies on app downloads and individual user switching</strong>, both of which have a higher cost floor. The offline restaurants are a compelling supply-side story. They do not, by themselves, generate demand. The risk is that Ownly onboards 70K restaurants across Bengaluru and finds that order volume doesn't distribute to the long tail — it concentrates in the same 3,000 restaurants that Zomato and Swiggy also serve well.</p>
      <p>Finally: <strong>Swiggy's decision to sell its 12% Rapido stake for ₹2,400Cr within weeks of Ownly launching is the single clearest external signal that Ownly is being taken seriously.</strong> When a competitor exits a ₹2,400Cr position rather than maintain a conflict, it's telling you something. That's a stronger endorsement of Ownly's threat potential than any analyst report or launch metric — and it's the number I'd put at the top of any Ownly funding pitch.</p>
      <p>This is a case study I'll keep updating. The real test isn't Bengaluru launch metrics — it's whether the model holds when Ownly enters its second and third city, where Rapido's network is thinner and the incumbent habits are deeper. That's when we find out if this is a structural play or a well-funded experiment.</p>
    </div>

  </div>
